00:22:41.590 --> 00:22:43.340 align:middle line:84%
and they all came up
with the same answer.

00:22:43.340 --> 00:22:48.760 align:middle line:84%
The question is, what is the
optimum amount of competition

00:22:48.760 --> 00:22:49.780 align:middle line:90%
in any environment?

00:22:49.780 --> 00:22:51.640 align:middle line:84%
Now, these are
scientists that rarely

00:22:51.640 --> 00:22:54.700 align:middle line:84%
use broad, sweeping
statements, but they do.

00:22:54.700 --> 00:22:56.170 align:middle line:84%
And what the
scientific paper said,

00:22:56.170 --> 00:22:58.690 align:middle line:84%
the optimum amount
of competition in any

00:22:58.690 --> 00:23:02.050 align:middle line:84%
environment-- in the
classroom, in the workplace,

00:23:02.050 --> 00:23:03.220 align:middle line:90%
on the playing field--

00:23:03.220 --> 00:23:04.560 align:middle line:90%
is zero.

00:23:04.560 --> 00:23:09.530 align:middle line:84%
That competition always,
always, always is destructive.

00:23:09.530 --> 00:23:11.950 align:middle line:84%
It's detrimental to the
individual and the community.

00:23:11.950 --> 00:23:16.030 align:middle line:84%
Cooperation and
mutual aid is the rule

00:23:16.030 --> 00:23:17.800 align:middle line:90%
that nature is based upon.

00:23:17.800 --> 00:23:22.150 align:middle line:84%
Very prestigious journals like
New Scientist, April 2008--

00:23:22.150 --> 00:23:25.450 align:middle line:84%
